# -*- encoding: utf-8 -*-
# Arc: WarriorPath | Scene: WarriorQueen7Calshure
# Source: C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\steamapps\common\The Survival of Sarah Rose\game\script.rpy

translate ru strings:

    old "Sarah sat atop one of the battlements of the city of Calshure."
    new "Sarah sat atop one of the battlements of the city of Calshure."

    old "With exception of the keep, most of the buildings in Calshure were build quite low, allowing her to look over the entire city."
    new "With exception of the keep, most of the buildings in Calshure were build quite low, allowing her to look over the entire city."

    old "She watched her army marching through the streets of the city, greeted as liberators."
    new "She watched her army marching through the streets of the city, greeted as liberators."

    old "The Tribesmen had fled the city by early hour, keeping true to their word."
    new "The Tribesmen had fled the city by early hour, keeping true to their word."

    old "The City Guard had opened the gates to the city, allowing her army to enter without so much as drawing steel."
    new "The City Guard had opened the gates to the city, allowing her army to enter without so much as drawing steel."

    old "Most of the Tribesmen had died in the battle."
    new "Most of the Tribesmen had died in the battle."

    old "A rare few were caught alive, mostly becaused they had been too wounded to fight to their deaths."
    new "A rare few were caught alive, mostly becaused they had been too wounded to fight to their deaths."

    old "For them, being captured was worse than death."
    new "For them, being captured was worse than death."

    old "Denied their glory."
    new "Denied their glory."

    old "Sarah watched as people threw themselves as the soldiers of her army."
    new "Sarah watched as people threw themselves as the soldiers of her army."

    old "Crying, desperate gratitude."
    new "Crying, desperate gratitude."

    old "It was hard for her to imagine what these people must have endured."
    new "It was hard for her to imagine what these people must have endured."

    old "To have lived under the control of the Tribesmen for years on end. Enduring their rule."
    new "To have lived under the control of the Tribesmen for years on end. Enduring their rule."

    old "From the corner of her eyes, Sarah saw a man walk up towards her."
    new "From the corner of her eyes, Sarah saw a man walk up towards her."

    old "His bronzed skin and un-Rosannan garb set him apart from most."
    new "His bronzed skin and un-Rosannan garb set him apart from most."

    old "Cassius."
    new "Cassius."

    old "I wondered where you might be."
    new "I wondered where you might be."

    old "The people are eager to meet you. It's all they talk about."
    new "The people are eager to meet you. It's all they talk about."

    old "Sarah sighed. She was tired."
    new "Sarah sighed. She was tired."

    old "I'll be down in a moment. I'm just...taking a breather."
    new "I'll be down in a moment. I'm just...taking a breather."

    old "No rush. They'll wait up all day if they have to, just to catch a glimpse."
    new "No rush. They'll wait up all day if they have to, just to catch a glimpse."

    old "Their great liberator."
    new "Their great liberator."

    old "Is that what they're saying?"
    new "Is that what they're saying?"

    old "Cassius nodded again."
    new "Cassius nodded again."

    old "I've been out among the citizens for a bit. Heard some stories of what it was like."
    new "I've been out among the citizens for a bit. Heard some stories of what it was like."

    old "If even half of it was true, then I can't blame them for being happy to be rid of the Tribesmen."
    new "If even half of it was true, then I can't blame them for being happy to be rid of the Tribesmen."

    old "Cassius spat."
    new "Cassius spat."

    old "Savage creatures."
    new "Savage creatures."

    old "Wish you'd given me a chance to meet them in battle though."
    new "Wish you'd given me a chance to meet them in battle though."

    old "What? Not a fan of the diplomatic option?"
    new "What? Not a fan of the diplomatic option?"

    old "I am a warrior first."
    new "I am a warrior first."

    old "If all the rulers of the world were like you, I'd never find work again."
    new "If all the rulers of the world were like you, I'd never find work again."

    old "Yes, a tragedy."
    new "Yes, a tragedy."

    old "Then you'd have to get a real vocation."
    new "Then you'd have to get a real vocation."

    old "Ah, yes. A farmer perhaps. Can you imagine me with a pitchfork?"
    new "Ah, yes. A farmer perhaps. Can you imagine me with a pitchfork?"

    old "You would make a terrible farmer."
    new "You would make a terrible farmer."

    old "Still, they make for good practice."
    new "Still, they make for good practice."

    old "Sarah looked at him and saw a few scratches on his body."
    new "Sarah looked at him and saw a few scratches on his body."

    old "Don't tell me they gave you any trouble."
    new "Don't tell me they gave you any trouble."

    old "Nothing so serious, but they're interesting fighters. Unique styles."
    new "Nothing so serious, but they're interesting fighters. Unique styles."

    old "Well, glad you got your fun out of it."
    new "Well, glad you got your fun out of it."

    old "And the dead?"
    new "And the dead?"

    old "The dead have won glory. Might we all be so lucky one day."
    new "The dead have won glory. Might we all be so lucky one day."

    old "Sarah couldn't tell if he was joking or serious. Perhaps both."
    new "Sarah couldn't tell if he was joking or serious. Perhaps both."

    old "Anyway, I just thought I'd let you know that they're ready for you in the main square."
    new "Anyway, I just thought I'd let you know that they're ready for you in the main square."

    old "Thanks. I'll be down in just a bit."
    new "Thanks. I'll be down in just a bit."

    old "She watched Cassius leave again."
    new "She watched Cassius leave again."

    old "Below she could hearing the growing murmurs of the crowd, gathering."
    new "Below she could hearing the growing murmurs of the crowd, gathering."

    old "She felt more hestitant to meet her own people than to meet her enemies on the battlefield."
    new "She felt more hestitant to meet her own people than to meet her enemies on the battlefield."

    old "But this too was a part of ruling."
    new "But this too was a part of ruling."

    old "Sarah pushed herself to her feet and began to make her way down the steps of the walls."
    new "Sarah pushed herself to her feet and began to make her way down the steps of the walls."

    old "Below, she could see the growing crowd, shouting and screaming as they began to spot her."
    new "Below, she could see the growing crowd, shouting and screaming as they began to spot her."

    old "She slightly waved."
    new "She slightly waved."

    old "Even that smallest of gesture was enough to solicit a roar from the crowd."
    new "Even that smallest of gesture was enough to solicit a roar from the crowd."

    old "As she descended from the last flight of stairs, she stepped out onto the improvised podium that had been build."
    new "As she descended from the last flight of stairs, she stepped out onto the improvised podium that had been build."

    old "Slowly she walked out onto the stage."
    new "Slowly she walked out onto the stage."

    old "With each step, the crowd grew louder and louder."
    new "With each step, the crowd grew louder and louder."

    old "She saw the square, filled with people, pressing up against one another, screaming out her name."
    new "She saw the square, filled with people, pressing up against one another, screaming out her name."

    old "As she looked over the crowd of people, she saw not just the whole of them, but the individuals."
    new "As she looked over the crowd of people, she saw not just the whole of them, but the individuals."

    old "The desperate, pleading eyes from and old man."
    new "The desperate, pleading eyes from and old man."

    old "The cheering, rapturous screams from a younger one."
    new "The cheering, rapturous screams from a younger one."

    old "An older woman, crying, clutching what seemed to be her daughter."
    new "An older woman, crying, clutching what seemed to be her daughter."

    old "So many different people, all brought together."
    new "So many different people, all brought together."

    old "Around her."
    new "Around her."

    old "Sarah trembled at the realization that all this worship on their faces was for her."
    new "Sarah trembled at the realization that all this worship on their faces was for her."

    old "Was she really worthy of this?"
    new "Was she really worthy of this?"

    old "Could any person be?"
    new "Could any person be?"

    old "Memories of her Father came to her. He had seemed worthy of it, in her estimation."
    new "Memories of her Father came to her. He had seemed worthy of it, in her estimation."

    old "But to compare herself to her Father still seemed to her mind as blasphemous."
    new "But to compare herself to her Father still seemed to her mind as blasphemous."

    old "Her people..."
    new "Her people..."

    old "Sarah raised one fist in the air, motioning the crowd to silence."
    new "Sarah raised one fist in the air, motioning the crowd to silence."

    old "Slowly, their cheers drifted away to whispers, and finally to silence."
    new "Slowly, their cheers drifted away to whispers, and finally to silence."

    old "The whole of the city seemed suddenly still."
    new "The whole of the city seemed suddenly still."

    old "People of Calshure!"
    new "People of Calshure!"

    old "People of Rosanna!"
    new "People of Rosanna!"

    old "The tyranny of the Tribes is over!"
    new "The tyranny of the Tribes is over!"

    old "Her declaration was met with loud cheers from the gathered citizens."
    new "Her declaration was met with loud cheers from the gathered citizens."

    old "Before today, most of you had never seen me."
    new "Before today, most of you had never seen me."

    old "But you have heard my name."
    new "But you have heard my name."

    old "You have heard the name of my family."
    new "You have heard the name of my family."

    old "Rose."
    new "Rose."

    old "Sarah studied their faces, seeing their recognition."
    new "Sarah studied their faces, seeing their recognition."

    old "I come before you, not to demand loyalty like kings of old, but to ask for your aid."
    new "I come before you, not to demand loyalty like kings of old, but to ask for your aid."

    old "We have won a great victory today, but this war is not yet over."
    new "We have won a great victory today, but this war is not yet over."

    old "Not while a foreign warlord sits upon the Throne of my family."
    new "Not while a foreign warlord sits upon the Throne of my family."

    old "Angry shouts could be heard across the square."
    new "Angry shouts could be heard across the square."

    old "Oaths of loyalty are easily sworn, and we speak them sometimes without thinking."
    new "Oaths of loyalty are easily sworn, and we speak them sometimes without thinking."

    old "But it is in times of great crisis, like the one we find ourselves in, that we are forced to confront the simple truths."
    new "But it is in times of great crisis, like the one we find ourselves in, that we are forced to confront the simple truths."

    old "Who has sworn oaths whose words weigh less than air."
    new "Who has sworn oaths whose words weigh less than air."

    old "And who here, by uttering their oaths, have wedded themselves to Nation and People, as surely as vows of marriage wed two souls to one another?"
    new "And who here, by uttering their oaths, have wedded themselves to Nation and People, as surely as vows of marriage wed two souls to one another?"

    old "Loud, approving cries, rose up from the crowd."
    new "Loud, approving cries, rose up from the crowd."

    old "Then I say to all of you today, with this war not yet won; I shall demand none of you to fight by threat of conscription."
    new "Then I say to all of you today, with this war not yet won; I shall demand none of you to fight by threat of conscription."

    old "I ask only..."
    new "I ask only..."

    old "Whom here pledges their lives willingly?"
    new "Whom here pledges their lives willingly?"

    old "A thunderous chorus rose up."
    new "A thunderous chorus rose up."

    old "Sarah watched as men leapt, throwing up their arms, eager to join her army."
    new "Sarah watched as men leapt, throwing up their arms, eager to join her army."

    old "She smiled, seeing how her army would swell from the influx of these new and eager recruits."
    new "She smiled, seeing how her army would swell from the influx of these new and eager recruits."

    old "Not trained in war, but any capeable hand could learn to swing a sword."
    new "Not trained in war, but any capeable hand could learn to swing a sword."

    old "And any eager man could be trained to kill."
    new "And any eager man could be trained to kill."

    old "She saw their faces painted with mad zeal, eager for war."
    new "She saw their faces painted with mad zeal, eager for war."

    old "And she would give them their desires."
    new "And she would give them their desires."

    old "A few hours had passed and night had fallen over the city of Calshure."
    new "A few hours had passed and night had fallen over the city of Calshure."

    old "Sarah was sitting behind her desk, working at preparing the orders to resume the march."
    new "Sarah was sitting behind her desk, working at preparing the orders to resume the march."

    old "Outside, she could hear the loud celebrations."
    new "Outside, she could hear the loud celebrations."

    old "Her soldiers were eager for some relaxation, and the citizens were overflowing with gratitude from being liberated from the Tribesmen."
    new "Her soldiers were eager for some relaxation, and the citizens were overflowing with gratitude from being liberated from the Tribesmen."

    old "From what few reports she had read, their occupation had been brutal."
    new "From what few reports she had read, their occupation had been brutal."

    old "The Tribesmen had never truly intended to rule over the land or the people. Not as genuine rulers."
    new "The Tribesmen had never truly intended to rule over the land or the people. Not as genuine rulers."

    old "They simply sat in their halls, extracting wealth and women, and putting down any resistance with brute force."
    new "They simply sat in their halls, extracting wealth and women, and putting down any resistance with brute force."

    old "Meanwhile, the yields of the nearby farms had collapsed and the local economy had likewise dwindled."
    new "Meanwhile, the yields of the nearby farms had collapsed and the local economy had likewise dwindled."

    old "Planting crops and raising livestock meant believing in a stable future."
    new "Planting crops and raising livestock meant believing in a stable future."

    old "The Tribesmen simply raided as they pleased."
    new "The Tribesmen simply raided as they pleased."

    old "Poverty. Starvation. Exploitation."
    new "Poverty. Starvation. Exploitation."

    old "These were all the Tribesmen had brought to her people."
    new "These were all the Tribesmen had brought to her people."

    old "And they had forever remained foreign to the people of Rosanna."
    new "And they had forever remained foreign to the people of Rosanna."

    old "They kept locked to their own keeps, having little interest in the people outside of what they could extract from them."
    new "They kept locked to their own keeps, having little interest in the people outside of what they could extract from them."

    old "And thus, there seemed few people if any in the city of Calshure that were sad to see the Tribesmen gone."
    new "And thus, there seemed few people if any in the city of Calshure that were sad to see the Tribesmen gone."

    old "Sarah continued her work."
    new "Sarah continued her work."

    old "There was so much to do."
    new "There was so much to do."

    old "She'd leave the celebrations to other people."
    new "She'd leave the celebrations to other people."

    old "She had to keep her momentum. Continue to march on the Capital as soon as possible."
    new "She had to keep her momentum. Continue to march on the Capital as soon as possible."

    old "The new recruits from Calshure would be a welcome addition to her army."
    new "The new recruits from Calshure would be a welcome addition to her army."

    old "Sarah went over a report from the chief medic."
    new "Sarah went over a report from the chief medic."

    old "They were already running dangerously low on medical supplies, just to deal with those currently wounded."
    new "They were already running dangerously low on medical supplies, just to deal with those currently wounded."

    old "The wounded soldiers lined up outside the triage tents."
    new "The wounded soldiers lined up outside the triage tents."

    old "Already there were not enough medics to treat everyone."
    new "Already there were not enough medics to treat everyone."

    old "Another loss like this and her army would be faced with some dire decisions."
    new "Another loss like this and her army would be faced with some dire decisions."

    old "Memories of the night before, replayed in her head."
    new "Memories of the night before, replayed in her head."

    old "She had gotten the city, but at the expense of her dignity."
    new "She had gotten the city, but at the expense of her dignity."

    old "Sarah prayed that everything that had transpired would remain a secret."
    new "Sarah prayed that everything that had transpired would remain a secret."

    old "If her people ever found out..."
    new "If her people ever found out..."

